Hi @Lorless,

This should definitely work with arrays. What you describe is correct – that it renders each path section as a string – but that's totally OK in javascript! In fact, javascript arrays are really just objects with normal string keys:

```js
console.log(typeof []);
// => object
```

They just take advantage of the fact that in javascript `1..toString() === "1"`, which means that when you use a number to access an "index" you're really just using its string representation to access the corresponding key! Try this out:

```js
var arr = ['a','b'];

console.log(arr[1]);
// => b

console.log(arr['1']);
// => b
```

You can see that accessing the index by either number or string work the same. If you continue to have issues, please reopen, but things should continue to work this way.

