I thought a bit about it, and I think the issue is [Widget. _split_state_buffers](https://github.com/ipython/ipywidgets/blob/6eed97c6bb9e8c6f62bd2c7ce39965844b811b0f/ipywidgets/widgets/widget.py#L261). It needs to go throught dicts and lists (similar to `_widget_to_json `) to see if they contain any `_binary_types` and `.pop` those, so it can be json'ed. Then the `buffer_keys` can also be a list of items, say `["x", "data"]`, so that on the js side, instead of simply assigning to `state[buffer_keys[i]] `, it should it nested, so in the above example it would effectively do `state[buffer_keys[i][0]][buffer_keys[i][1]] = buffers[i]`. Lists would then also naturally be supported.
This would make things really flexible and fast. 

