@deckar01 Indeed, documentation says that message argument can be dictionary, BUT that means that inside dictionary you have errors for nested fields. What I mean is that the error message itself should be string, not a complex structure describing particular error (like ```{'code': 123, 'message': 'Houston, we have a problem'}```)
As I said in commit comments, #442 is backward incompatible only in a way that it disallows some non-documented usage which accidentally worked before (although I'm not sure anyone has abused it to such extent).
I suggest merging #442 and then dive into whatever discussion you like. If you plan to change validation interface anyways, merging this one won't hurt anyone.

On the other hand, I still believe the indexable approach can stay in place, it can be convenient for some weird case, when a user has a self defined class, that supports indexing and length, but does not support iteration.
```python
    class MyClass(object):
        def __init__(self, indexable_container):
            self.indexable_container = indexable_container

        def __getitem__(self, index):
            logging.debug("value at index", index, "was accessed")
            return self.indexable_container[index]

        def __len__(self):
            return len(self.indexable_container)
```

The idea is that for iterators the states are independent form each other, but for indexation this might not be the case.

