@raulchen  One problem with that is how to determine that all the tasks and actors of a given job have completed, if we untie task/actor lifecycle from driver. 

We need to know job completion in order to properly cleanup stuff in gcs and plasma, and to return properly status when user queries job status.  Looks like it needs information from all the node managers, to make sure that there are no remaining tasks for a given job, querying GCS is not sufficient as it only contains finished/running tasks. It seems like we'd have a service which periodically queries node managers on whether a job is finished? 

An alternative way is to divide jobs into two categories: jobs that completes itself, and jobs that are long running and are supposed to be killed explicitly. In the former case actor lifecycle is still bound to driver, and in the latter case we allow actors to run after driver terminates, until the job is killed explicitly from portal. There are also some complexities in this case though.

